ng, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Kent","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: habitational name from the county of Kent. The surname is also established in Ireland, where English bearers of this name settled in Meath, in the 13th century. The name has been Gaelicized as <b>Ceannt</b>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Wakehurst","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Wakehurst Place in Ardingly (Sussex)."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Wakehurst of Kent was born in 1180, in England. She married Sir Richard Rici Wakehurst before 1198, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died about 1218, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1180–about 1218":"1180–umbes 1218","1178–1198":"1178–1198","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1180–1218":"1180–1218","1215":"1215","about 1218":"umbes 1218","before 1198":"enne 1198","1178":"1178","1198":"1198","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","1218":"1218","Wakehurst, Kent, England":"Kent, Ing